Release 2.25.3
Update ibus-typing-booster.pot (Only line number changes)

Add a feature to change the line direction of bidi text

Resolves: https://github.com/mike-fabian/ibus-typing-booster/issues/500

This is done by adding or removing LRM (U+200E LEFT-TO-RIGHT MARK) or
LRM (U+200F RIGHT-TO-LEFT MARK) characters.

To make it work correctly, ibus-typing-booster needs to know in which application
the user is typing:

- if it is firefox, libreoffice (soffice), or google-chrome, it cannot work
  because these applications already enforce a default direction for input buffers.
  Therefore, if typing booster is able to detect that one of these applications
  is used, it does not change the current line, this would just insert useless
  RLM or LRM markers.
- To preserve the cursor position, typing booster needs to know whether it is
  a Gtk or a Qt application. Because Qt applications move the cursor logically
  within a bidi string when the arrow keys are pressed but Gtk applications
  do it visually. Therefore, to make it work in Gtk apps, it is necessary
  to detect that is Gtk but unfortunately this sometimes fails, often shortly
  after the start of a new desktop session.
  On top of that, when typing booster knows that it is GTK, it also
  needs to be able to do bidi reordering to figure out how many arrow
  keys are needed. To do the bidi reordering, typing booster uses
  https://pypi.org/project/PyBidi/, if that is not installed, the
  cursor position always jumps to the end of the line when changing
  the line direction. So please install https://pypi.org/project/PyBidi/
  if you want to test this.
- if it is a Gtk4 application like gnome-text-editor using the input module
  'gtk4-im', then forward_key_event() does not work so there is no way
  to correct the cursor positon.
- in Gnome Wayland it does not seem to work well at the moment

Other problems:

- surrounding text needs to be fully supported. Therefore, it cannot work in
  gnome-terminal or xfce4-terminal for example.
- A surrounding text event needs to have happend since the current window got focus.
  If no surrounding text event has happened yet, get_surrounding_text() sometimes
  returns surrounding text from the previous window which would mess up things completely.
  Therefore, typing booster does nothing until a surrounding text event has happened.
  Usually (but apparently not always?) a surrounding text event happens when
  something is typed (or the arrow keys are used) or the cursor is moved with the mouse.
  I am not sure why it sometimes still doesn’t happen.

If this feature doesn’t seem to work, check

tail -F ~/.local/share/ibus-typing-booster/debug.log | grep -E '_change_line_direction'

while trying to use it, the log messages from the _change_line_direction() should
give insights on what went wrong.

Line direction
Improve Unicode version checking in itb_emoji.py

add a _prepare_return_from_do_process_key_event() to remember some stuff from the last key event processing

It seems more consistent to remember this stuff for all key events, not only for those
when self._process_key_event(key) was called.
Use `r` before regexp string
Display key values in hexadecimal when printing debug messages
Use IBus.KEY_VoidSymbol instead of 0xffffff
Update the emoji data files to the draft version of Unicode 16.0.0
Update UnicodeData.txt to the Unicode 16.0.0 draft as of 2024-02-09.

Release 2.25.0
Update ibus-typing-booster.pot (Only line number changes)
Fix a few pylint warnings

Add new combobox option “Record mode”

Resolves: https://github.com/mike-fabian/ibus-typing-booster/issues/470

Chooses which words to record (words are called “phrases” in the source code for historic reasons):

    0: Everything
    1: Correctly spelled or previously recorded
    2: Correctly spelled
    3: Nothing

I left the existing option

    ☑️ Off the record mode

there for the moment. It works as it always did. Setting the new
“Record mode” option to 3 and checking “Off the record mode” does the
same thing so this seems a bit redundant.  But the advantage is that
one can quickly toggle recording to off using “Off the record mode”
with a keybinding and when toggling it on again return to the
operation of the selected “Record mode” in the combobox option.

I could maybe remove the option “3: Nothing” from the combobox to remove redundancy…

As I added one more row to the options tab of the setup tool, I saved one
row by putting the two buttons

[ Learn from text file ] [ Delete learned data ]

into the same row.
Add a `phrase_exists()` function
Add some comments
Simplify two debug messages (.encode('UTF-8') makes no sense anymore)
